---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BarChart from '../../../components/BarChart.astro';
import KeyFigure from '../../../components/KeyFigure.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Net Fiscal Impact of Immigration: 20-Country Comparison | Immigration Factbook" lang="en" altHref="/themes/cout-fiscal/" description="Official data on the net fiscal impact of immigration across 20 Western countries. Treasury, central banks, OECD primary sources only." type="Dataset">

<main class="theme-page">
  <div class="page-header">
    <nav class="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/en/">Immigration Factbook</a> <span>›</span> <span>Compare by Theme</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>Net Fiscal Impact of Immigration — 20-Country Official Data Comparison</h1>
    <p class="intro">
      This page compiles official estimates of the net fiscal cost or contribution of immigration published by national governments, central banks, and international organizations. Methodologies, population scopes, and time horizons differ significantly between countries — direct number-to-number comparisons require caution. "No official data available" means no official estimate was found at the time of research, not an omission by this site.
    </p>
    <p class="intro-sub">
      Very few countries conduct systematic, repeated fiscal accounting in the manner of Denmark's Finance Ministry. Most have only one-off studies, partial estimates, or research institution analyses. This is a structural limitation of international comparison.
    </p>
    <div class="lang-switch">
      <a href="/themes/cout-fiscal/">🌐 日本語で見る</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="charts-section">
    <div class="key-figures-row">
      <KeyFigure value="−DKK 16bn/yr" label="Denmark: net fiscal cost of non-Western immigrants (Finance Ministry, 2023)" />
      <KeyFigure value="−€2.1bn/yr" label="Germany: net fiscal cost of 2015 refugee cohort (DIW/IAB)" />
      <KeyFigure value="+$900bn" label="USA: cumulative federal deficit reduction from immigration surge (CBO, 2024)" />
    </div>

    <BarChart
      title="Net Fiscal Cost / Contribution by Country (approx. €bn equivalent)"
      unit="Bn€"
      bars={[
        { label: 'Netherlands (cumulative 1995–2019)', value: -400, note: 'van de Beek et al. / CBS microdata' },
        { label: 'Austria (post-2015 asylum migrants)', value: -8.1, note: 'EcoAustria, cumulative through 2020' },
        { label: 'Germany (2015 refugee cohort)', value: -2.1, note: 'DIW/IAB, annual avg. through 2030' },
        { label: 'Denmark (non-Western immigrants)', value: -3.6, note: 'Finance Ministry, DKK 27bn/yr ≈ EUR' },
        { label: 'Sweden (all foreign-born)', value: -0.6, note: 'Konjunkturinstitutet, SEK 6bn/yr' },
        { label: 'Austria (all migration forms)', value: 1.4, note: 'EcoAustria, cumulative through 2020' },
        { label: 'Italy (annual)', value: 1.2, note: 'Fondazione Leone Moressa, 2024 report' },
        { label: 'Belgium (all immigrants)', value: 3.0, note: 'OECD International Migration Outlook' },
      ]}
      sourceLabel="National Finance Ministries, OECD, research institutions (see country pages)"
      sourceUrl="/en/themes/fiscal-cost/"
      sourcePrefix="Source: "
    />
    <p class="chart-note">
      ⚠️ Methodologies differ significantly: the Netherlands figure is a 1995–2019 cumulative lifetime present value; other figures are annual flows or specific-period cumulative totals. Direct comparison requires caution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="table-section">
    <h2>Fiscal Cost / Contribution: Country-by-Country Official Data</h2>
