    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="methodological-note">
    <h2>What this data does not show</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Methodologies differ across countries — figures cannot be directly compared between nations.</li>
      <li>Net fiscal impact varies greatly by migrant profile (work, refugee, family) and length of stay.</li>
      <li>Fiscal cost is only one dimension of immigration's effects. Labour market, demographic, and cultural contributions are not captured here.</li>
      <li>Some countries have no official estimates, making comparisons partial.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="methodology-note">
    <h2>Important Caveats for Comparison</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Static vs. dynamic accounting</strong>: Annual tax-minus-spending approaches (static) and lifetime present value approaches (dynamic) produce very different results. Denmark and Australia use dynamic/lifetime approaches.</li>
      <li><strong>Population scope</strong>: Some countries cover all immigrants; others cover only specific cohorts (refugees, recent arrivals) or visa categories.</li>
      <li><strong>Government level</strong>: The US CBO estimate is federal only and excludes state/local costs. Australia explicitly notes that fiscal benefits accrue federally while infrastructure costs fall on states.</li>
      <li><strong>Commissioning body</strong>: Studies commissioned by government ministries, employer associations, and private foundations may differ in assumptions and emphasis. Funding sources are noted in each country page.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</main>

<style>
  .theme-page {
